'''<U+017D>u<U+017E>i Jelinek''' (born '''Suzana Ferber'''; July 17, 1920, Budapest)<ref>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=Prgomet|first=Ivana|coauthors=|title=Jovanka Broz: Drugarice Jelinek, volim va<U+0161>e cipele|pages=|publisher=[[24sata (Croatia)|24sata]]|date=2008-06-20|url=http://www.24sata.hr/show/jovanka-broz-drugarice-jelinek-volim-vase-cipele-67898|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> is [[Croatia]]n well-known fashion stylist, designer and writer.

==Early life==
Jelinek was born in [[Budapest]] to poor [[Jew]]ish parents, Izidor and Ru<U+017E>a Ferber, as a youngest of three children. Her parents were both deaf. Jelinek father was from [[Ludbreg]], and her mother was from [[Hungary]]. They met in Budapest, where they were sent by their families, to the only specialized school for deaf people in the area.<ref name=vl>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=Bo<U+017E>i<U+0107>|first=Tanja|coauthors=|title=<U+017D>u<U+017E>i Jelinek: U 92. pi<U+0161>em knjigu "<U+017D>ivjeli mu<U+0161>karci"|pages=|publisher=[[Ve<U+010D>ernji list]]|date=2012-048-15|url=http://www.vecernji.hr/scena/zuzi-jelinek-u-92-pisem-knjigu-zivjeli-muskarci-clanak-398266|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> Jelinek also had two brothers. After Jelinek birth, her family moved to [[Zagreb]]. They lived in a poor part of a town. Although her aunt, father's sister, was married to a wealthy Zagreb Jew, Jelinek said that her family didn't benefit from it. Jelinek aunt was ashamed of her poor and deaf brother, so when Jelinek family visited, she would receive them in the kitchen because they were not good enough for the salons in the house. At that time Jelinek sworn that she will become someone in the life. Humiliation experienced in the childhood poverty, were incentive that she gets a hold of a decent life. She graduated from the Zagreb School of tailors.<ref name=hrt/><ref name=vl/><ref name=jl2>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=Bolan<U+010D>a|first=Sandra|coauthors=|title=Moj savjet svim <U+017E>enama: Svakoga si jutra recite da ste mlade, lijepe i sretne|pages=|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=2011-08-11|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/template/article/article-print.jsp?id=965157|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref><ref name=sd>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=Celevska|first=Ivan<U+010D>ica|coauthors=|title=<U+017D>u<U+017E>i Jelinek: Nemoralne ponude prihvatite s 50 godina|pages=|publisher=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|date=2011-08-07|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.com/Linija-X/tabid/243/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/145399/Default.aspx|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref>

==Career and later life==
Jelinek was only 17 years of age whe she began to work in [[Paris]] as a seamstress in a factory of [[Nina Ricci (designer)|Nina Ricci]]. While in Paris, Jelinek met [[Coco Chanel]], for which she briefly worked. Because of the [[World War II]], Jelinek returned to Zagreb in 1939. In Zagreb she opened a tailor shop, where she sewed for a wealthy Jewish families. Jelinek was also active in language learning. In 1941 she meet and married her first husband, Zagreb dentist Dr. Erich Jelinek. From that marriage Jelinek has two children, son Ivica and daughter Dijana.<ref name=jl2/><ref name=vl/>

With the [[Independent State of Croatia]] establishment in 1941, the infamous [[Usta<U+0161>e]] policy soon led her brothers in the camps where they were both killed, one in [[Kerestinec]] concentration camp and second in [[Jadovno concentration camp]].<ref name=vl/> While in [[Su<U+0161>ak]], where she moved to escape the Usta<U+0161>e and [[Nazi]] persecution, Jelinek learned that her parents will be taken to [[Jasenovac concentration camp]]. She went to the Italian officer who she seduced, and so saved her parents from the deportation. During the war Jelinek joined the [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]]. After the war she began to sew again, and with 40 years of age she moved to [[United States]].<ref name=jl2/>

In United States she sewed, and was very successful at it. When she returned to Zagreb, Jelinek found out that her husband left her for maidservant. She continued to work hard and travel the world. That, however, bothered [[Josip Broz Tito]]. Tito called her and said that she can't travel and promote her models as <U+017D>u<U+017E>i Jelinek, because it's not good for [[workers' self-management]] in [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], and offered her to become the director of the Macedonian fashion company Teteks. Jelinek refused such offer. In 1962, during a speech, Tito named her as a negative element in Yugoslavia and was told to leave. She took her children and parents in the car, and moved to [[Geneva]]. On arrival, Jelinek got into a street and asked for the cheapest apartment for her family. Today, in that same street, she has four houses. She returned to Zagreb in 1964, when Tito invited her to come home. After her arrival, she sewed fashion creations for Tito's wife, [[Jovanka Broz]]. During her career, Jelinek sold fashion creations in the United States, [[Japan]] and all of [[Europe]].<ref name=jl2/><ref name=jl4>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=|first=|coauthors=|title=<U+017D>u<U+017E>ina <U+017E>ivotna pri<U+010D>a sti<U+017E>e na male ekrane|pages=|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=2007-06-14|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/zuzina-zivotna-prica-stize-na-male-ekrane/178478/|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> 

Jelinek wrote 8 books and is regular columnist for Croatian women's magazine [[Gloria (magazine)|Gloria]] since 1994.<ref name=sd/><ref name=jl3>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=Mirkovi<U+0107>|first=Nada|coauthors=|title=<U+017D>u<U+017E>i Jelinek: <U+2018>Mu<U+0161>karci su zbog feminizma postali oholi: <U+010D>ekaju da <U+017E>ene njih osvoje<U+2019>|pages=|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=2010-05-16|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/zuzi-jelinek---muskarci-su-zbog-feminizma-postali-oholi--cekaju-da-zene-njih-osvoje-/774065/|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] recorded the documentary which recounts the life of Jelinek during early life poverty and later success.<ref name=jl4/> A few years ago Jelinek received an offer from [[Steven Spielberg]], who wanted to make a film about her life, because he heard the story of a single Jewish women during [[The Holocaust|the Holocaust]], who risked a life to save her parents when she realized that they could be taken to the concentration camp. Spielberg invited her for the chief adviser in the movie, but although she was very flattered by the offer, Jelinek declined it with conclusion that she has too little time to set aside for two years of life United States.<ref name=jl4/> Jelinek resides in her real estates in Zagreb, Geneva and [[Opatija]]. After her first husband, Jelinek married three more times.<ref>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=Jelinek|first=<U+017D>u<U+017E>i|coauthors=|title=Ljubav kao kamen smutnje|pages=|publisher=[[Gloria (magazine)|Gloria]]|date=|url=http://gloria.com.hr/kolumne/zuzi.php?id=82|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> Currently she is in the fourth marriage with Milorad Ronkulin.

Jelinek is longtime member of the council of the Jewish community in Zagreb.<ref name=jl5>{{hr icon}} {{Cite news|last=Pavi<U+010D>i<U+0107>|first=Darko|coauthors=|title=Dr. Kraus: Sinagogu <U+0107>emo graditi sami!|pages=|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=2006-11-06|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/template/article/article-print.jsp?id=161191|accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref>

==Published works==
